      "markdown": "# Article \n\n## Organizing principles of astrocytic nanoarchitecture in the mouse cerebral cortex\n\nChristopher K. Salmon, ${ }^{1,6,7}$ Tabish A. Syed, ${ }^{3,5,6}$ J. Benjamin Kacerovsky, ${ }^{1,6}$ Nensi Alivodej, ${ }^{1}$ Alexandra L. Schober, ${ }^{1}$ Tyler F.W. Sloan, ${ }^{4}$ Michael T. Pratte, ${ }^{1}$ Michael P. Rosen, ${ }^{1}$ Miranda Green, ${ }^{1}$ Adario Chirgwin-Dasgupta, ${ }^{1}$ Shaurya Mehta, ${ }^{2}$ Affan Jilani, ${ }^{2}$ Yanan Wang, ${ }^{2}$ Hojatollah Vali, ${ }^{5}$ Craig A. Mandato, ${ }^{5}$ Kaleem Siddiqi, ${ }^{2,5, *}$ and Keith K. Murai ${ }^{1,6, *}$<br>${ }^{1}$ Centre for Research in Neuroscience, Department of Neurology \\& Neurosurgery, Brain Repair and Integrative Neuroscience Program, The Research Institute of the McGill University Health Centre, Montreal General Hospital, 1650 Cedar Avenue, Montreal, QC H3G 1A4, Canada<br>${ }^{2}$ School of Computer Science and Centre for Intelligent Machines, McGill University, 3480 Rue University, Montreal, QC H3A 2A7, Canada<br>${ }^{3}$ MILA - Qu√©bec Al Institute, 6666 Rue Saint-Urbain, Montreal, QC H2S 3H1, Canada<br>${ }^{4}$ Quorumetrix Studio, Montreal, QC H1T 2H5, Canada<br>${ }^{5}$ Department of Anatomy \\& Cell Biology, McGill University, 3640 Rue University, Montreal, QC H3A 0C7, Canada<br>${ }^{6}$ These authors contributed equally<br>${ }^{7}$ Twitter: @cksalmo<br>${ }^{8}$ Lead contact<br>*Correspondence: siddiqi@cim.mcgill.ca (K.S.), keith.murai@mcgill.ca (K.K.M.) https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cub.2023.01.043\n\n## SUMMARY\n\nAstrocytes are increasingly understood to be important regulators of central nervous system (CNS) function in health and disease; yet, we have little quantitative understanding of their complex architecture. While broad categories of astrocytic structures are known, the discrete building blocks that compose them, along with their geometry and organizing principles, are poorly understood. Quantitative investigation of astrocytic complexity is impeded by the absence of high-resolution datasets and robust computational approaches to analyze these intricate cells. To address this, we produced four ultra-high-resolution datasets of mouse cerebral cortex using serial electron microscopy and developed astrocyte-tailored computer vision methods for accurate structural analysis. We unearthed specific anatomical building blocks, structural motifs, connectivity hubs, and hierarchical organizations of astrocytes. Furthermore, we found that astrocytes interact with discrete clusters of synapses and that astrocytic mitochondria are distributed to lie closer to larger clusters of synapses. Our findings provide a geometrically principled, quantitative understanding of astrocytic nanoarchitecture and point to an unexpected level of complexity in how astrocytes interact with CNS microanatomy.\n\n## INTRODUCTION\n\nAstrocytes are essential regulators of central nervous system (CNS) development and function. They play vital roles in processes ranging from respiration to memory recall. ${ }^{1}$ The functional versatility of astrocytes stems from their anatomical complexity and ability to integrate signals from most CNS cell types/structures, including neurons and vasculature. Gray matter astrocytes are believed to have a \"sponge-like\" anatomy, with perforations forming holes and loops. ${ }^{2}$ It is also thought that astrocytic processes form progressively smaller elements termed branches, branchlets, and leaflets. ${ }^{3-5}$ However, a deeper quantitative analysis of astrocytic structure is required to understand how their complex architecture enables such specialized and diverse physiological roles. ${ }^{6,7}$ Higher-resolution datasets and methodologies that can effectively interrogate the complex geometry and architecture of astrocytes are needed.\n\nThe convoluted processes that make up an astrocyte's structure can be as thin as 10 nm and fall below the detection limits by confocal and super-resolution microscopy, ${ }^{6,8}$ necessitating electron microscopy and serial sectioning at extremely thin\nslicing intervals. ${ }^{9,10}$ However, astrocytes can be up to $100 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ in diameter. This range in scale makes wholistic studies of astrocytic structure difficult. One readily identifiable astrocytic structure is the perisynaptic astrocytic process (PAP), which interacts with and regulates synapses. ${ }^{11}$ PAPs are assumed to occur at branch tips, where they detect synaptic activity ${ }^{12}$ and possibly deliver neuroactive molecules such as ATP, glutamate, and D-serine. ${ }^{13}$ However, whether PAPs have unique structural properties is unknown. Defining such anatomical features will aid the understanding of how astrocytes interact with synapses to regulate synaptic transmission. Astrocytes also have specialized endfeet (EF) that ensheath neurovasculature to support blood-brain-barrier (BBB) maintenance and neurovascular coupling. ${ }^{14,15}$ However, a complete and quantitative picture of this distinctive structure is lacking.\n\nHere, we deployed astrocyte-tailored computer vision methods on new high-resolution datasets to make accurate structural measurements of astrocytes. Using geometric measures, we decompose astrocytes into previously unnoticed building blocks, which we term constrictions, expansions, and cores. We show that these building blocks are assembled into"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "hierarchical branching structures rather than a sponge-like reticulum. PAPs are composed of a unique subset of these building blocks. We also show that astrocytes partition the neuropil, interacting with astrocyte-defined synaptic clusters (ADSCs), and that astrocytic mitochondria are positioned closer to larger ADSCs. This finding points to a new, unexpected level of complexity in brain organization. Our study also makes available a series of computational tools new to cell biology, which are well suited for studying astrocytes and other cell types of any level of complexity.\n\n## RESULTS\n\n## Resolving and quantifying astrocytic nanoarchitecture\n\nThere are two main impediments to quantifying astrocytic nanoarchitecture. First, astrocytes have an irregular anatomy composed of nanoscopic processes that confocal and superresolution light microscopy cannot fully resolve, even when using membrane-targeted labels (Figures 1A and 1B). ${ }^{4,16}$ Second, there is a dearth of methods capable of interrogating astrocytic structural complexity. Important observations have been made using qualitative approaches and indirect measurements of astrocytic structure. ${ }^{3,17-20}$ However, a systematic analysis of the 3D astrocytic structure requires specialized computational approaches for accurate structural measurements.\n\nTo address these impediments, we developed a pipeline for systematic, quantitative analyses of astrocytic nanoarchitecture (Figures 1C-1E). We used focused ion beam scanning electron microscopy (FIB-SEM) to produce uninterrupted series of layer $2 / 3$ mouse somatosensory (S1) cortex (mill depth $=8 \\mathrm{~nm}$, axial resolution $=4.13 \\mathrm{~nm}$; Figures 1C and 1D). Fine astrocytic processes were clearly resolved while providing a sufficiently wide field of view to image large subvolumes containing neuropil and perivascular subcompartments (Figure 1F). Large volumes of astrocytes were manually segmented yielding three astrocytic reconstructions from three mice, with perivascular EF, mitochondria, endoplasmic reticulum (ER), and postsynaptic densities (PSDs) also segmented (Figures 1H, 1I, and S1;Videos S1, S2, and S3).\n\n## Fundamental building blocks and architectural\n\n## signatures of layer 2/3 astrocytes\n\nReconstructed astrocytic processes had distinct thick and thin regions and did not simply taper progressively toward their tips. We therefore developed an approach for describing astrocytic nanostructure, where, moving inward from the fine tips of processes, we decomposed the astrocyte into constituent \"parts.\" We defined measures of protrusiveness and thickness for every vertex in a 3D mesh describing an astrocytic surface (Figures 2A, 2B, and S1A-S1E). Using these measures, we identified thin, local surface protrusions that corresponded to tips. We then simulated surface flows, using a fast-marching method, ${ }^{21}$ beginning at tips and ending at thick, core regions. Moving progressively along the length of processes, we located boundaries between parts at regions of abrupt change in thickness. From this we classified fundamental part types composing the astrocyte: thin \"constrictions\" present at process tips and within the branching structure, thicker \"expansions,\" and the thickest trunk- or pillar-like \"core\" regions (Figures 2C and 2D). This unveiled a small number of core regions representing large processes (maximum thickness\n\n836 nm ) giving rise to a complex array of thinner processes (Figures 2C, S1F, and S1G). A repeating motif of expansions separated by constrictions became apparent (Figure 2E). The proportions of surface-mapped geometric measurements (Figures 2F and S1E) and part types (Figures 2F and S1H) were consistent across astrocytes, as were surface areas, volumes, and surface area-to-volume ratios (S/V) of constrictions and expansions (Figures 2G and S1I). This was also true for thickness-protrusiveness measurements (Figure 2H). Astrocyte 3 showed slight but significant differences in thickness (Figure 2H) that may be related to it being a larger, more complete sample, fully embedded in neuropil, as opposed to being near other structures such as a blood vessel, like astrocyte 2 (Figures S1B and S1C). We also compared the distribution of local widths of astrocyte 3 to that of the apical dendrite, and associated obliques, of a layer 5 somatosensory mouse neuron. ${ }^{22}$ This portion of a dendritic arbor, although it contains many thin regions such as spine necks and heads, is skewed significantly thicker than the portion of the astrocyte we examined, reflecting the thin, space-filling nature of astrocytic processes (Figure 2I). The maximal thicknesses were 0.8 and $2.02 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ for astrocyte 3 and the dendrite, respectively. Meshed and voxelized astrocytic models showed consistent fundamental parts (Figure S1J). Together, these results suggest that layer $2 / 3$ astrocytes have a quantifiable, consistent nanostructural composition.\n\nHow does SEM sectioning interval impact detection of fine astrocytic structures? In astrocytes 1, 2, and 3, respectively, 18\\%, $22 \\%$, and $32 \\%$ of vertices were on regions with a thickness $<50 \\mathrm{~nm}$, while $45 \\%, 45 \\%$, and $57 \\%$ were on regions with a thickness $<70 \\mathrm{~nm}$. Only $0.04 \\%, 2.3 \\%$, and $2.5 \\%$ of surface points were on regions with a thickness $<29 \\mathrm{~nm}$, respectively. To simulate how larger sectioning intervals affect astrocytic reconstructions, we omitted layers used to generate them. Processes were lost at intervals above 8 nm , and this was exacerbated at larger intervals (Figures 2J and S2A). While the overall volume of the remaining structures was not drastically altered with increasing interval size (Figure 2K), the number of separated components rose steeply, especially at intervals $>30 \\mathrm{~nm}$ (Figure 2L). This fragmentation was a consequence of splitting of the astrocytic volume at locally thin regions. We also considered viewpoint invariant radii of astrocytic processes to estimate parts that could be potentially lost when sectioning in any plane (Figures S2B and S2C). Large numbers of parts stand to be lost, particularly at intervals $>30 \\mathrm{~nm}$, impacting structural interpretation and connectivity analysis of astrocytes. Thus, thin serial sectioning intervals are essential for accurate representation of astrocytic nanostructure.\n\nTo quantitatively describe the organization of astrocytic structure (i.e., whether they are sponge-like or have strictly hierarchical branching), we interpreted cores, expansions, and constrictions as nodes in a directed graph. Starting at core regions, edges were directed outward toward connecting parts in a recursive manner until a terminal part was reached. The resulting graphs revealed shallow but wide networks of astrocytic parts: astrocyte 3, the most complete section of astrocyte, was composed of 13 hierarchical levels, while individual levels contained up to 331 distinct parts (Figures 3A, 3B, and S3A-S3D). Connectivity hubs giving rise to many other parts were apparent. Examining the numbers of edges extending from each node (outdegree) confirmed this (Figures 3C-3H). While the large majority"
