      "markdown": "of parts connected to 5 or fewer other parts (Astro1 94.3\\%; Astro2 96.0\\%; Astro3 96.1\\%), a small number of hubs gave rise to up to 45 connected parts (Figures 3D and 3E). Hubs were formed exclusively by cores and expansions (Figure 3F) and were larger than lower connectivity parts (hubs $7.5 \\times 10^{6} \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{3}$, nodes $1.9 \\times$ $10^{7} \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{3}, \\mathrm{p}=0.0014$; Figures 3C and 3G). The latter was also true when only expansions were considered (expansion hubs $0.23 \\pm$ $0.031 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{3}$, expansion nodes $0.046 \\pm 0.0038 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{3}, \\mathrm{p}=5.4 \\times$ $10^{-11}$; Figure 3H). Thus, layer 2/3 astrocytes are organized hierarchically in a wide but shallow network with major connectivity hubs.\n\nAstrocytes are described as being sponge-like with a perforated architecture containing abundant holes and loops, ${ }^{23-27}$ which may facilitate $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ spread. ${ }^{28}$ Evidence for these structures is based on impressions from light microscopy or lowerresolution EM visualizations and is not founded on quantification of 3D astrocytic shape. Addressing this, we generated 3D centerline curve skeletons from astrocytic models to detect holes and loops. Of $>1,000$ putative holes across three datasets, most were due to minute tracing inaccuracies, such as missing voxels, that did not otherwise affect astrocytic shape analysis. We visually inspected 512 putative holes that could not be easily filtered out as missing voxels based on size. We encountered a small number of apparent holes in the models ( $\\sim 500 \\mathrm{~nm}$ diameter) in the vicinity of dendritic spines. However, these were almost always associated with extremely thin regions of the astrocyte in which membranes were pinched together and excluded cytoplasm (Figures S3E-S3G). Due to our segmentation conventions, regions lacking visible cytoplasm were not traced. Importantly, these ambiguous holes did not have other structures passing through them. Of the 512 putative holes, only 3 were bona fide holes (Figure 3I). By contrast, astrocytic processes that wrap around microanatomy without forming truly connected loops were more frequently observed (Figure 3J). We also encountered juxtaposed membranes/processes from the same astrocyte that were not fused (Figure 3K). Overall, our data show that astrocytes consist of independent processes of undulating thickness, emanating from a small number of core regions and hubs, and ending at terminal parts without forming extensive holes or looping structures. This is uncharacteristic of sponge morphology. ${ }^{29}$\n\n## The structure of PAPs\n\nPAPs, also referred to as the glial component of the tripartite synapse, have been characterized in numerous studies. ${ }^{10,30-33}$ However, little is known about what, if any, unique astrocytic\nstructures form PAPs. Qualitative examination of astrocytic compartments in contact with synapses ( $n=416$ ) in segmented datasets did not reveal conspicuous features such as vesicles or particular arrangements of organelles. Our continuous segments of astrocytes allowed assessment of PAP geometry in relation to the surrounding astrocytic structure. We segmented all PSDs in contact with the astrocytic surface ( $n=3$ astrocytic volumes), yielding 2,107 PSDs with expected characteristics (Figures S4AS4D). Using a fast-marching method, ${ }^{21}$ we evolved 3D wavefronts from every PSD to the astrocytic surface to find the geodesic (i.e., shortest path) between the two structures (Figure 4A; Videos S1, S2, and S3). Each geodesic, and hence each PSD, was associated with a contact point on the neighboring PAP (Figure 4B). The majority of contact points occurred at the synaptic cleft (cleft $=94 \\%$, spine $=4 \\%$, axonal bouton $=$ $1 \\%, n=416$; spine and axon contact points were $96.3 \\pm 10 \\mathrm{~nm}$ from cleft through extracellular space). Distances between synapses and PAPs (Figure S4E) were similar in scale to previous reports. ${ }^{34,35}$ We then cross-referenced PSD-PAP contact points against measures of astrocytic nanostructure. The classical view of PAPs places them at tips of astrocytic processes. ${ }^{23,25,36,37}$ To test this assumption, we determined the proportion of astrocytic parts that could be classified as terminal (tips), embedded (flanked on either side), or core (Figure 4C). We used node degree to separate terminal parts (indegree $=1$; outdegree $=0$ ) from embedded parts (outdegree $\\geq 1$ ). The majority of parts were terminal parts, as opposed to embedded parts flanked on either end by other parts ( terminal, $61.5 \\% \\pm 1.9 \\%$; embedded, $38.5 \\% \\pm 1.9 \\% ; \\mathrm{p}=0.0009$; Figure 4D). Constrictions were mainly at terminals but still accounted for an appreciable number of embedded parts (terminal constrictions, $79.1 \\% \\pm$ $2 \\%$; embedded constrictions, $20.9 \\% \\pm 2 \\% ; \\mathrm{p}<0.001$ ), whereas expansions were almost exclusively embedded (terminal, $3.5 \\% \\pm 0.1 \\%$; embedded, $96.5 \\% \\pm 0.1 \\% ; \\mathrm{p}<0.001$; Figure 4E). As synapses are evenly distributed within cortical layers, ${ }^{38}$ we asked if PSD contact points would distribute evenly on the astrocytic surface. The majority of contact points were on embedded parts (terminal, $34 \\% \\pm 3 \\%$; embedded, $57 \\% \\pm 1 \\%$; core, $8 \\% \\pm$ $3 \\% ; \\mathrm{p}<0.001$; Figure 4F). This is likely due to the fact that embedded parts account for almost all expansions, which occupy more surface area and volume (Figures 2F and 2G). To account for this volume factor and investigate whether PSD contact points were distributed randomly on the astrocytic surface, we compared contact points with sets of randomly placed points on the surface ( 33 sets of points per astrocyte, each set equal in number to PSD contact points for that astrocyte). Random point\n\n[^0]\n[^0]:    Figure 2. Decomposition of astrocytes into constituent parts\n    (A and B) Protrusion and thickness scores mapped onto astrocyte 3, respectively.\n    (C) Identification of astrocytic parts (cores, blue; expansions, purple; constrictions, yellow).\n    (D) Top, gallery view of cores, expansions, and constrictions. Bottom, probability density distribution of maximum thickness or protrusion score by part.\n    (E) Examples of constriction-expansion-constriction structural motif.\n    (F) Proportion of vertices (V) and parts (P) represented by cores, expansions, and constrictions.\n    (G) Comparison of expansions and constrictions, based on surface area, volume, and surface-to-volume ratio.\n    (H) Comparison of thickness (nm) and protrusiveness ( $\\mathrm{n}=3$ astrocytes in F-H).\n    (I) Comparison of LS somatosensory neuron apical dendrite (red) and astrocyte 3 thickness scores across all vertices.\n    (J) Fragmentation of astrocyte 1 at larger slicing intervals (disconnected components in magenta).\n    (K and L) (K) Volume of largest remaining structure and (L) number of separated components with increasing interval size. KS test performed in (I), ${ }^{* * *} \\mathrm{p}<0.00001$. Elsewhere, ${ }^{*} \\mathrm{p}<0.05,{ }^{* *} \\mathrm{p}<0.01$, and ${ }^{* * *} \\mathrm{p}<0.001$.\n    See also Figures S1 and S2 and Videos S1 and S3. Scale cube, $1 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{3}$ in (B), (C), and (E)."
