      "markdown": "sampling was area-weighted to account for variation in vertex density. This revealed an overrepresentation of contact points on constrictions and an underrepresentation on expansions and cores, compared with randomly placed points on the astrocytic surface (constrictions: $53 \\% \\pm 2.4 \\%$ PSD contact points, $39 \\% \\pm 0.2 \\%$ random surface points; expansions: $38.6 \\% \\pm$ $0.9 \\%$ PSD, $46 \\% \\pm 0.02 \\%$ random; cores: $8 \\% \\pm 3.2 \\%$ PSD, $15 \\% \\pm 0.1 \\%$ random; $\\mathrm{p}<0.0001$; Figure 4G). This overrepresentation on constrictions was driven by embedded constrictions (Figures 4H and 4I). Accordingly, PSD contact points fell on vertices with higher protrusiveness and lower thickness (Figures 4J, S4F, and S4G). However, contact points were found across the entire distributions of thickness/protrusiveness scores (Figure 4J), reflecting the presence of contact points, and thus PAPs, on all part types and locations (Figures 4F and 4G). Thus, although PAPs are often terminal constrictions, this is not a rule; they are also embedded deeper within the hierarchy of the astrocytic structure, with both constrictions and expansions forming en-passant PAPs. We also asked whether certain synapse categories were more likely to be contacted by constrictions or expansions (Figure S4H). This was not the case, although expansions contacted a population of synapses with larger PSDs (constriction PSDs $1.77 \\pm 0.06 \\times 10^{6} \\mathrm{~nm}^{3}$, expansion PSDs $2.01 \\pm 0.08 \\times 10^{6} \\mathrm{~nm}^{3}$, core PSDs $1.79 \\pm$ $0.14 \\times 10^{6} \\mathrm{~nm}^{3}, \\mathrm{p}=0.05$; Figure S4I). Thus, while constrictions account for the majority of PAPs, expansions preferentially form PAPs with larger, and likely stronger, more active synapses. The increased volume of expansions may increase capacity for neurotransmitter/ion homeostasis at these larger synapses.\n\n## Astrocytic mitochondria, ER, and MERCs differ between EF and nEF regions\n\nAstrocytic mitochondria are important for $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ signaling and energy production. ${ }^{39,40}$ Investigating mitochondrial ultrastructure in astrocytes, we divided astrocytic models into perivascular EF and \"non-endfoot\" (nEF) regions that interface with the neuropil (Figures S1C and S1D). Here, we added a fourth reference volume containing a capillary with EF. While nEF mitochondria were largely composed of short and long tubules, EF mitochondria were flattened (Figure 5A). EF mitochondria had lower surface $\\mathrm{S} / \\mathrm{V}(\\mathrm{EF}=14.5 \\pm 0.7, \\mathrm{nEF}=18.6 \\pm 1.2, \\mathrm{p}=0.0076$; Figure 5B), lower surface curvatures ( $\\mathrm{EF}=0.014 \\pm 0.001, \\mathrm{nEF}=0.018 \\pm$ $0.001, \\mathrm{p}=0.0018$; Figure 5C), and were thicker ( $\\mathrm{EF}=190.5 \\pm$ $12.6 \\mathrm{~nm}, \\mathrm{nEF}=148.9 \\pm 11.6 \\mathrm{~nm}, \\mathrm{p}=0.022$; Figure 5D) than nEF mitochondria. EF mitochondria were thinned toward their centre, with a concave surface (Figures 5E-5G). Thus, mitochondrial structure in astrocytes relates to mitochondrial location and may reflect functions specific to those locations. For example, increased mitochondrial diameter may minimize production of reactive oxygen species under conditions of excessive nutrient supply, ${ }^{41,42}$ potentially explaining the particular shape of EF mitochondria.\n\nMitochondria work with ER to regulate $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ signaling/homeostasis and lipid biosynthesis. ${ }^{33}$ We therefore reconstructed large\nparts of the ER network (Figure 5H). ER in nEF regions mostly consisted of a polygonal array of tubules (Figure S5A) connected by three-way junctions as described. ${ }^{44}$ By contrast, ER in EF formed large, sheet-like cisterns (Figure 5H). To compare the amounts of ER tubules vs. cisterns, we analyzed surface curvature ${ }^{45}$ and found that EF ER, where sheet-like cisterns predominated, had smaller total curvature (Figures S5A-S5C). ER cisterns in EF were at times arranged in two layers, with one layer facing the capillary in close apposition to the adluminal astrocytic membrane. Mitochondria were nestled between two ER sheets, forming extensive mitochondria-ER contact sites (MERCs), often along their flattened portions (Figure 5Hii). Occasionally, ER tubules passed through the centre of flat mitochondria, highlighting a tight interaction between these EF organelles (Figures 5Hi and 5Hiii). MERCs are important sites for $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ exchange and lipid and protein biosynthesis, and they are altered in disease. ${ }^{46}$ Investigating the differences between MERCs in EF and nEF regions, we compared the area of mitochondrial outer membrane contributing to MERCs (Figure 5I). ${ }^{47} \\mathrm{EF}$ MERCs were larger than those in nEF regions ( $\\mathrm{EF}=0.14 \\pm$ $0.03 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{2}, \\mathrm{nEF}=0.038 \\pm 0.005 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{2}, \\mathrm{p}=0.0005$; Figure 5J). MERC coverage of EF mitochondria was nearly double that of nEF mitochondria ( $\\mathrm{EF}=18.3 \\% \\pm 2.5 \\%, \\mathrm{nEF}=9.3 \\% \\pm 1.1 \\%$, $\\mathrm{p}=0.006$; Figure 5K). The more extensive MERCs in EF may relate to heightened metabolic need at the neurovascular interface. ${ }^{48}$ Overall, our results demonstrate specific structural adaptations of astrocytic mitochondria, ER, and MERCs in astrocytic subcompartments.\n\n## Structural properties of excitatory synapses do not influence their proximity to the astrocytic surface or mitochondria\n\nAs mitochondria give rise to a significant portion ( $\\sim 25 \\%-30 \\%$ ) of $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ events in astrocytes, ${ }^{39}$ play a central role in energy metabolism, and display activity-related mobility related to glutamate transporter activity, ${ }^{49}$ we hypothesized that astrocytic mitochondrial position is influenced by nearby synapses (Figure 6A). To test this, we computed geodesics from PSDs to their nearest contact points on the astrocytic surface (Figures 4A and 4B; Videos S1, S2, and S3). We then made distance measurements by evolving a 3D wavefront from mitochondria, outward to the astrocytic surface (Figure 6B; Video S4) to measure geodesics through the convoluted intracellular space of astrocytes. The sum of PSD-Astro and Astro-Mito distances gave PSD-Mito distances (Figures 6A and S6A). PSD-Mito distances had variable, multimodal distributions (Figures S6B and S6C). PSD-Astro distances were small ( $0.36 \\pm 0.31 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ Astro1; $0.32 \\pm 0.017 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ Astro2; $0.29 \\pm 0.01 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ Astro3; Figure S6F), and thus PSD-Mito distances were similar to Mito-Astro distances (Figure S6G). Previous work suggested that mitochondria are excluded from PAPs, with a minimal distance of $\\sim 500 \\mathrm{~nm}$ between PSDs and any astrocytic $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ source. ${ }^{20}$ However, we found that synapses varied widely in their proximity to astrocytic mitochondria, ranging from 162.1 nm to $>23.0 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ (Figure S6C). PSD volume\n\n[^0]\n[^0]:    (I-K) Example reconstructions and micrographs of (I) a true hole, (J) a wrapping structure, and (K) juxtaposed astrocytic membranes. Astrocyte, yellow; axon/ presynaptic terminal, magenta; dendrite/spine, green. Arrowheads point to a hole in (I), fine tips of a wrapping structure in (J), and juxtaposed astrocytic membranes in (K). Scale cube, 250 nm edges in (C). ${ }^{*} \\mathrm{p}<0.01$ and ${ }^{* * *} \\mathrm{p}<0.0001$. See also Figure S3 and Video S3."
