      "markdown": "did not correlate with mitochondrial proximity (Figure S6D). Furthermore, no PSD attributes (asymmetric/symmetric; spine/ shaft; presence/absence of spine apparatus; macular/perforated) were associated with distances to their nearest mitochondrion (Figure S6E). These results suggest that PSDs predicted to be associated with stronger synapses (i.e., larger, perforated PSDs with spine apparatuses ${ }^{59-63}$ ) do not lie closer to astrocytic mitochondria relative to astrocytic space.\n\n## Identification of ADSCs\n\nWe observed that PSDs group around certain astrocytic subregions (Figure 6C) and hypothesized that astrocytes form specialized arrangements with clusters of synapses. Given the lack of established ground truth for such synaptic clusters, and given the high degree of astrocytic complexity, a parameter-free, unsupervised clustering approach was required to isolate these clusters. We employed dominant sets (Dsets) clustering, which has been used for a variety of spatial clustering problems and requires only a similarity matrix as input. ${ }^{53-55}$ Using a fast-marching approach, we calculated PSD-to-PSD pairwise distances to obtain distance matrices for all PSDs in each astrocytic volume (Figures 6D, 6E, and S7A). Applying a customized Dset clustering algorithm to the resulting distance matrices revealed that synapses form discrete ADSCs based on distances from one another, ranging in size from 4 to 55 PSDs per cluster (Figures 6F-6H). Since ADSCs are based on PSD-PSD distance measured through the astrocyte, discrete astrocytic subregions are associated with each cluster (Figure 6G). Cluster size did not correlate with the proportion of different synapse categories represented therein (symmetric proportion vs. cluster size, $r^{2}=$ $-0.003, \\mathrm{p}=0.3$; shaft vs. size, $\\mathrm{r}^{2}=-0.01, \\mathrm{p}=0.7$; spine apparatus vs. size, $r^{2}=-0.03, p=0.09$; perforation vs. size, $r^{2}=$ $-0.01, p=0.6$ ), nor did cluster size correlate with PSD volume within clusters ( $r^{2}=-0.009, p=0.2$ ). To demonstrate that astrocytic morphology played the operant role in defining ADSCs, we clustered PSDs based solely on their distances from one another (Euclidean distance) as a negative control, ignoring the astrocyte. This yielded a distinct set of clusters with different mean pairwise distances between their PSDs when compared with the \"intravolume\" PSD-PSD distances through the astrocytic cytoplasm (intravolume $11.1 \\pm 0.67 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$, Euclidean $5.74 \\pm$ $0.19 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}, \\mathrm{p}=1.9 \\times 10^{-13}$ ). This is expected owing to the convoluted astrocytic morphology. Thus, our data suggest that astrocytes partition the synaptic space, creating ADSCs. This indicates that synapses relate to one another based on how astrocytes interact with them, in addition to where they fall in Euclidean space and within a neural circuit.\n\n## ADSCs predict the location of astrocytic mitochondria\n\nWhile individual synapses and synapse types did not lie closer to astrocytic mitochondria, it is possible that ADSCs have a spatial link to astrocytic mitochondria. Remarkably, cluster size was inversely correlated with the mean distance of mitochondria to\nthe PSDs in that cluster (Figure 7A). This suggests that astrocytic mitochondria are positioned closer to larger ADSCs. The same was true when clustering was performed on distances between PSDs measured along the astrocytic surface, rather than through the cytoplasm (Figure S7B). This effect was present whether or not symmetric PSDs were excluded (Figure S7C). These results were largely replicable with k-means and density-based spatial clustering of applications with noise (DBSCAN) clustering algorithms, which require parameters to be chosen a priori (Figure S7D). PSD clusters based on the Euclidean PSD-PSD distances (neglecting the astrocyte) did not show a similar correlation (Figure S7B), demonstrating that astrocytic morphology is key to the relationship between ADSCs and astrocytic mitochondria.\n\nTo verify that larger synaptic clusters do not lie closer to astrocytic mitochondria simply by virtue of taking up more space, we repeated the analysis while omitting shorter PSD-Mito distances from each cluster (Figure 7B). When omitting the shortest $50 \\%$ of distances, the shortest $75 \\%$ of distances, or all but the single longest PSD-Mito distances per cluster, the correlation between cluster mean PSD-Mito distance and cluster size remained. This indicates that large clusters as a whole are located more closely to mitochondria, rather than just a subset of their PSDs. Additionally, PSDs close to the edge of the reference volumes may be more appropriately sorted into clusters centered outside the dataset. They may also be closer to mitochondria just outside the dataset. To account for this, we progressively removed PSDs from the edges of the datasets by iteratively shrinking the bounding box of the volumes, excluding PSDs that fell outside the new bounding box. As the population of PSDs considered was eroded, the summary data for the resulting cluster mean PSD-Mito distance vs. cluster size correlation remained significant and relatively stable (Figures 7C and S7E). This indicates consistency in the relationship between ADSCs and PSD-Mito distances and that PSDs on the edge of the volumes do not alter the relationship. As a whole, our results suggest that astrocytes form higher-order interactions with clusters of synapses (rather than with individual synapses), and ADSCs predict the location of astrocytic mitochondria.\n\n## DISCUSSION\n\nAstrocytes are complex cells with seemingly countless thin and convoluted processes. Using FIB-SEM and astrocyte-tailored computer vision methods, we resolved the geometry of astrocytes and their nanoarchitectural framework. Our analyses relied on measurements using fast-marching methods, accurate geodesics, and medial curves to uncover the fundamental building blocks of astrocytes and their assembly into hierarchical networks. These tools also revealed specific structural characteristics of PAPs and EF/nEF organelles. Finally, applying unbiased clustering, we discovered that astrocytes partition the local microenvironment and interact with synaptic clusters, or\n\n[^0]\n[^0]:    (H and I) Proportions of contact points vs. random points on (H) terminal or (I) embedded parts.\n    (J) Distributions of protrusiveness (top) and thickness (bottom) values when considering all vertices (yellow) or only PSD contact points (blue), astrocyte 3, Kolmogorov-Smirnov test, ${ }^{* * *} \\mathrm{p}<0.0001$. In (D)-(F) and PSD contact point proportions in (G)-(I), $\\mathrm{n}=3$ astrocytes. Scale cube, 250 nm edges. ${ }^{\\dagger} \\mathrm{p}<0.05,{ }^{* *} \\mathrm{p}<0.01$, and ${ }^{* * *} \\mathrm{p}<0.001$.\n    See also Figure S4 and Video S3."
