    {
      "markdown": "ADSCs, which bear a specific relationship to astrocytic mitochondria. These results provide insight into how astrocytes are constructed, form hierarchical networks with minimal looping structures, have distinct mitochondria/MERC architecture at EF, and how they possess a consistent architecture across datasets with constrictions and expansions that infiltrate the CNS and contact synapses. This specific structure of astrocytes has implications for how they pervade the local microenvironment and how they control the distribution of organelles, receptors, and signaling molecules that impact processes including $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ diffusion and synaptic function.\n\nAside from PAPs and EF, astrocytes do not display obvious structures akin to those found on neurons, such as axonal/dendritic branches, synapses, presynaptic boutons, and spines. Using shape analysis, we decomposed astrocytes into fundamental building blocks (constrictions, expansions, and cores). Astrocytes have been qualitatively described as consisting of branches, branchlets, and leaflets. However, this does not capture the alternating pattern of constrictions and expansions we observed, and it underestimates the depth of astrocytic hierarchical structure (Figures 3A, 3D, and S3). As process diameter can dictate the spread of $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ signals in astrocytes, with thinner diameter favoring decreased flux, increased propagation, and lower propagation failure rates, ${ }^{29}$ the alternating constriction-expansion arrangement may spatially constrain local $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ signals and be partly responsible for astrocytic microdomain $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ events.\n\nThe astrocytes we examined rarely contained holes or loops. Extensive, small astrocytic loops or \"rings\" have been reported near synapses, using super-resolution light microscopy. ${ }^{23,56}$ However, our automated, medial curve-based approach to locate loops in our datasets uncovered only three true loops. We did encounter cases where thinning of astrocytic processes could not be definitively discerned from small perforations. This thinning, in addition to processes that wrap other structures without forming loops, may account for the apparent rings observed at lower resolutions. These findings challenge the widely held view that astrocytes are spongiform, sponge-like, or have a reticular anatomy. Recent work examining astrocytic reflexive processes concludes that because some astrocytic processes loop back and contact themselves without fusing, the structure is indeed sponge-like, if not precisely spongiform or reticular. ${ }^{30}$ However, the lack of cytoplasm continuity in reflexive processes likely has functional implications for $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ signaling in astrocytic processes: few to no looping connections would limit $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ spread, perhaps biasing $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ dynamics toward localized events. We suggest dispensing with the imprecise sponge analogy and instead using established mathematical terminology for describing mazes. Purely hierarchically branching structures with no loops are referred to as \"simply connected\" or \"perfect\" mazes. Neurons are examples of perfect mazes. Astrocytes are thus nearly perfect mazes with very sporadic, local holes. Indeed, following the tortuous network of astrocytic processes evokes the sense of being lost in a maze.\n\nAstrocytic $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ events relate to neural activity ${ }^{57,58}$ and are needed for synaptic transmission/plasticity. ${ }^{59,60}$ Astrocytic mitochondria are one source of such $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ events. ${ }^{39}$ Given that astrocytic mitochondria can be repositioned, but are largely static in vivo, ${ }^{61}$ we asked whether astrocytic mitochondria preferentially localize near synapses. Although single synapses did not influence mitochondrial position, we found that synapses cluster around discrete astrocytic subregions creating ADSCs, and that ADSCs relate to mitochondrial placement in astrocytes. Thus, ADSCs constitute a CNS structural unit with potential relevance to neural circuit function. While functional synaptic clusters localized to individual dendrites have been observed, ${ }^{62,63}$ neither functional nor structural ADSCs have been reported. Theoretical frameworks have proposed that astrocytes form functional \"synaptic islands,\" whereby an astrocyte regulates thousands of synapses as a group. ${ }^{36,64}$ However, recent work suggests that $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ microdomains localized to astrocytic processes may respond to and regulate local clusters of synapses to enhance hippocampal place coding. ${ }^{65}$ Furthermore, depolarization of an astrocytic process following nearby synaptic activity can modulate glutamate uptake. ${ }^{66}$ This points to reciprocal regulation between astrocytic processes and groups of synapses clustered around them. ADSCs provide an enticing structural correlate to these functional synaptic clusters surrounding astrocytic processes that have emerged, but which, up to this point, had not been resolved anatomically. Local regulation of ADSCs may allow astrocytes to tune functional units of synapses with respect to local contexts such as clustered synaptic inputs from particular neurons, neuronal types, or brain regions.\n\nThe distance between mitochondria and synapses in an ADSC decreased with increasing ADSC size. This spatial relationship suggests yet a further level of complexity in CNS organization. While studies in neurons show that mitochondria are recruited to areas of heightened activity, the structural complexity of astrocytes complicates similar experimentation in astrocytes. ${ }^{67}$ In vitro evidence, using bath application of pharmacological agents, suggests mitochondrial mobility/positioning is coupled to glutamate uptake and $\\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ influx. ${ }^{49,67}$ However, local interventions, for instance, focal application of glutamate or glutamate transporter blockers, or local silencing/ablation of synapses, are needed to elucidate signals that regulate astrocytic mitochondrial positioning. Furthermore, as mitochondria, ER, and MERCs differ between EF and the nEF regions where astrocytes interact with ADSCs, local signals that define the shape/function of organelles in different subcompartments need exploration. Astrocytes also regulate synapse and circuit formation, ${ }^{68}$ and mitochondria become less motile as development progresses. ${ }^{61}$ This raises interesting developmental/mechanistic questions. Do developing synaptic clusters instruct astrocytic ramification, or do astrocytes determine which synapses form/persist in a cluster? Do synaptic clusters recruit mitochondria, or does mitochondrial placement promote synaptic cluster formation/consolidation? Do these processes rely on neuronal activity and sensory\n\n[^0]\n[^0]:    (J and K) Comparison of (J) MERC size and (K) fraction of mitochondrial surface occupied by MERCs, in endfeet and non-endfoot regions. MERC comparisons performed with Welch's unequal variance $t$ test. Scale bars: 400 nm in SEM in (E), (G), and (H). Scale cube, 500 nm edges in (H). ${ }^{*} \\mathrm{p}<0.05,{ }^{* *} \\mathrm{p}<0.01$, and ${ }^{* * *} \\mathrm{p}<0.001$.\n    See also Figure S5 and Video S2."
