      "markdown": "![img-9.jpeg](img-9.jpeg)\n\nFigure 7. Proximity of mitochondria to ADSCs\n(A) Mean PSD-Mito distance within ADSCs are negatively correlated with ADSC size in the three astrocytic volumes studied.\n(B) Correlation of mean cluster PSD-Mito distance with ADSC size for the full complement of PSD-Mito paths (full), PSD-Mito paths above the median length (median), above the top quartile of PSD-Mito paths (Q4), and the single longest PSD-Mito paths per cluster (max distance).\n(C) Correlation metrics as PSDs were incrementally removed from the outside of the volume inward, by shrinking the bounding box for PSD inclusion while maintaining the astrocyte and mitochondrial surfaces constant. * $p<0.05$ and ${ }^{* * *} \\mathrm{p}<0.001$.\nSee also Figure S7.\nfor preserving extracellular space, but systematic characterization of new preservation techniques on astrocytic ultrastructure is required. ${ }^{63}$ Future analysis of larger datasets prepared with attention to the unique requirements of astrocytes will lead to a more complete picture of whole-cell astrocyte nanoarchitecture.\n\nThe findings presented here, along with the wealth of evidence establishing astrocytes as active players in neural circuit function, emphasize the need for more complete characterization of the intricacies of astrocytic nanoarchitecture. Astrocytes and neurons are partners in CNS function, and therefore unraveling their mutual relationships and interactions with other CNS microanatomy is central to understanding the brain.\n\n## STAR $\\cdot$ METHODS\n\nDetailed methods are provided in the online version of this paper and include the following:\n\n- KEY RESOURCES TABLE\n- RESOURCE AVAILABILITY\n- Lead contact\n- Materials availability\n- Data and code availability\n- EXPERIMENTAL MODEL AND SUBJECT DETAILS\n- METHOD DETAILS\n- In Utero Electroporation\n- DNA Constructs\n- Perfusion and tissue preparation for light microscopy\n- Electron microscopy sample preparation\n- FIB-S