    {
      "markdown": "# Data and code availability \n\n- All data reported in this paper will be shared by the lead contact upon request.\n- Original code has been deposited at https://github.com/murailab/NANO.git and is publicly available as of the date of publication.\n- Any additional information required to reanalyze the data reported in this paper is available from the lead contact upon request.\n\n\n## EXPERIMENTAL MODEL AND SUBJECT DETAILS\n\nExperiments using male and female mice (see method details for specific information) were approved by the Montreal General Hospital Facility Animal Care Committee and followed the guidelines of the Canadian Council on Animal Care. Mice were housed on a 12:12 inverted light:dark cycle and cared for according to standard operating procedures at McGill University and the Research Institute of the McGill University Health Centre.\n\n## METHOD DETAILS\n\n## In Utero Electroporation\n\nIn utero electroporation (IUE) was performed largely as previously described. ${ }^{84}$ Timed-pregnant female CD1 mice were purchased from Charles River Laboratories (Saint Constant, QC). Surgeries were performed on embryonic day 18. Pregnant mice were anesthetized using isoflurane and kept on a homothermic warming pad. An incision along the abdomen was made to expose the uterine horns containing embryos. After exposing the uterine horns, embryos were periodically flushed with warm ( $37^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$ ) sterile PBS (Gibco, Thermo Fisher, Waltham, MA). Using pulled borosilicate pipettes that were bevelled with diamond lapping film (FOSCO, Fremont, CA), $3 \\mu \\mathrm{l}$ of DNA mixture was injected into the lateral ventricles. Precise injection volume was attained with a foot pedal-controlled Elite Nanomite syringe pump (Harvard Apparatus, Holliston, MA). The DNA mixture contained $1 \\mu \\mathrm{~g} / \\mu \\mathrm{l}$ PB-GfaABC ${ }_{1} D$-Lck-mCherry to label astrocytic plasma membranes, $1 \\mu \\mathrm{~g} / \\mu \\mathrm{l}$ PB-GfaABC1D-mitoDendra2 to label astrocytic mitochondria, and $1 \\mu \\mathrm{~g} / \\mu \\mathrm{l}$ transposaseexpressing PB200PA-1 (Clontech, Takara Bio, USA; SBI Systems Bioscience, Palo Alto, CA). To help visualize the injection of the DNA mixture, $0.1 \\%(\\mathrm{w} / \\mathrm{v})$ of Fast Green dye (Millipore Sigma, Oakville, Ontario) was added to the solution and adjusted to the final volume with sterile PBS. Following injection of the DNA, 3 mm tweezer-electrodes were used to apply $3 \\times 50 \\mathrm{~ms} 42 \\mathrm{~V}$ pulses at 950 ms intervals via an ECM 830 square pulse generator (BTX, Holliston, MA). After injection of all the embryos, the uterine horns were placed back inside the abdomen and the incision site sutured. Pregnant mice were returned to their home cage and given post-surgical analgesics for 3 days and monitored until full recovery.\n\n## DNA Constructs\n\nAstrocytes and their precursors divide rapidly throughout postnatal development which makes episomal plasmid delivery less favorable due to the dilution of the DNA and low efficiency of gene expression following IUE. With the PiggyBac transposon system, DNA constructs are integrated into chromosomal DNA, thus resulting in stable gene expression. PiggyBac plasmids were purchased from SBI Systems Bioscience (Palo Alto, CA). All DNA constructs used for astrocyte targeted expression were manually cloned into the transposon plasmid (PB513B-1) under control of the modified human GFAP promoter, GfaABC ${ }_{1} D$ using restriction cloning and InFusion HD assembly (Clontech, Takara Bio, USA). The following sequence elements were obtained from Addgene: GfaABC ${ }_{1} D$ (\\#19974), Lck (\\#34924), and mitoDendra2 (\\#55796). The mCherry sequence was originally obtained from a plasmid donated by Dr. Roger Tsien (UCSD). DNA was prepared using the endotoxin-free NucleoBond Xtra Maxi EF kit (Clontech, Takara Bio, USA).\n\n## Perfusion and tissue preparation for light microscopy\n\nElectroporated mice ( 6 months old; male and female; CD1) were anesthetized with isoflurane and tissue fixed by transcardial perfusion first with ice cold DPBSfollowed by $4 \\%$ paraformaldehyde in 0.1 M phosphate buffer ( pH 7.4 ) at $5 \\mathrm{ml} / \\mathrm{min}$ for 5 minutes. Brains were removed and post-fixed in the same solution overnight at $4^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$. Following equilibration in $30 \\%$ sucrose in DPBS, the tissue was embedded in OCT (Somagen, Edmonton, AB) and snap frozen. Brains were cryosectioned coronally at $30 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ thickness and stored in DPBSat $4^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$ until use. Sections were mounted onto charged Superfrost√† Plus glass slides and preserved with SlowFade Gold Antifade Mountant (Thermo Fisher, Waltham, MA). Confocal microscopy was performed using an Olympus FV1000 laser scanning confocal microscope with a 60x oil-immersion objective (N.A. 1.4) at a resolution of $0.132 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{2} /$ pixel. Stuctured Illumination Microscopy (SIM) image stacks were acquired using a Zeiss LSM880 ElyraPS1 microscope with a 63x oil-immersion objective (PlanApochromat 63x/1.40 Oil DIC). All images were obtained using 5 rotations and processed for SIM using the Zeiss Zen software.\n\n## Electron microscopy sample preparation\n\nPostnatal day 50 adult male C57/Bl6 mice were anaesthetized with ketamine-xylazine cocktail and transcardially perfused with 910 ml of 0.1 M phosphate buffer (PB) at room temperature (RT) at $7 \\mathrm{~mL} / \\mathrm{min}$, followed by $210-280 \\mathrm{~mL}$ perfusion with $2.5 \\%$ glutaraldehyde, $2 \\%$ formaldehyde, 0.1 M PB at $7 \\mathrm{~mL} / \\mathrm{min}$. Brains were post-fixed in the same fixative solution at $4^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$ for 6-12 hours. Tissue chunks containing somatosensory (S1) cortex were manually dissected based on visible landmarks using straight razor blades and"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "cut into $300 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ slices using a vibratome. The tissue was then washed 3 times in 0.1 M sodium cocodylate buffer and stained with $1.5 \\%$ potassium ferrocyanide and $1 \\%$ osmium tetroxide/ 0.1 M cocodylate for 30 min . Tissue was washed again in ddH20 twice for 5 min , and block stained in $1 \\%$ uranyl acetate in ddH20 for 30 min and washed twice with ddH20. Tissue was passed through an acetone/ddH20 dehydration series of $30 \\%, 50 \\%, 70 \\%, 80 \\%, 90 \\%$ and $3 \\times 100 \\%$ acetone for 2 min at each step. This was followed by an epon infiltration series of $1: 1,2: 1$ and $3: 1$ epon:acetone for 30 min at each step. Tissue was left in $100 \\%$ epon for 6 hours before being allowed to harden at the point of a conical mold at $65^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$ for 24 hours. Thin sections were prepared and stained with toluidine blue to select the area for imaging. Ultrathin sections were examined by transmission electron microscopy on a Tecnai 12 BioTwin 120kV TEM equipped with an AMT XR80C CCD Camera (FEI, Hillsboro, OR) to assess tissue and staining quality.\n\n# FIB-SEM \n\nFIB-SEM imaging was performed as described previously. ${ }^{85}$ Briefly, Epon blocks containing tissue from four mice were trimmed with a razor blade to expose the region of interest, and were then mounted on a $45^{\\circ}$ pre-titled SEM stub and coated with a 4 mm layer of platinum to enhance electrical conductivity. Gallium ion beam milling of serial sections and block face imaging after each mill were carried out on a Helios Nanolab 660 DualBeam system using Auto Slice \\& View G3 ver 1.5.3 software (FEI, Hillsboro, OR). The sample block was first imaged to determine the orientation of the block face and ion and electron beams. A protective platinum layer $80 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ long, $19 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ wide and $2 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ thick was deposited on the surface orthogonal to the block, where the ion beam is first incident, to protect the sample from ion beam damage and to correct for stage and/or specimen drift. Trenches were milled on both sides of the region of interest to minimize re-deposition of milled material during automated milling and imaging. Fiducial markers were generated for both ion and electron beam imaging and were used to dynamically correct for drift in the $x$ - and $y$-directions during data collection by applying appropriate scanning EM beam shifts. Milling was carried out at 30 kV with an ion beam current of 9.3 nA , stage tilt of $6.5^{\\circ}$, and working distance of 4 mm . At each step, 8 nm of the block face was removed by the ion beam. This mill depth was chosen to ensure resolution of the smallest astrocytic processes while still collecting images of an appreciable volume. Each newly milled block face was imaged simultaneously with the Through the Lens Detector (TLD) for backscattered electrons and In-Column Detector (ICD) at an accelerating voltage of 2 kV , beam current of 0.4 nA , stage tilt of $44.5^{\\circ}$, and working distance of 3 mm . The pixel resolution was 4.13 nm with a dwell time of $30 \\mu \\mathrm{~s}$ per pixel. Pixel dimensions of the recorded image were $3072 \\times 2048$ pixels. The acquired image stacks from different mice measured $12.7 \\times 8.5 \\times 4.4 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ for Volume 1 ( 551 images), $12.7 \\times 8.5 \\times 5.4 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ for Volume 2 ( 672 images) and $12.7 \\times 8.5 \\times 7.8 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ ( 976 images). A fourth dataset ( 635 images) was collected to add additional endfeet from another mouse to the analysis.\n\n## 3D Reconstructions\n\nTrakEM2 was used for stack alignment and segmentation. ${ }^{86}$ Astrocytes were identified by clear cytoplasm devoid of visibly oriented microtubules, the presence of dark staining glycogen granules, and the absence of synaptic inputs (personal communication with Dr. Spacek). ${ }^{9}$ Astrocytic mitochondria also stained more lightly than neuronal mitochondria. Due to the extremely fine, convoluted processes of astrocytes, extensive quality control (QC) was required. Reconstructions correspond to $1 / 30^{\\text {In }}, 1 / 75^{\\text {In }}$ and $1 / 200^{\\text {In }}$ of a single astrocyte (Astro $3734.55 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{3}$, Astrocyte $2314.39 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{3}$, Astrocyte $1127.09 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}^{3}$ ) based on a whole astrocyte volume of $30,500 \\mathrm{~nm}^{3}$ and $30 \\%$ shrinkage of SS cortex after glutaraldehyde fixation. ${ }^{87}$ Two to four rounds of QC were performed (see supplemental information). Occasionally processes were so thin that cytoplasm could not be distinguished due to reduced resolution of the scanning EM approach. Tracing was stopped at these junctures. 3D models were generated using Blender and MATLAB.\n\n## Astrocyte segmentation quality control\n\nTo perform QC, we overlaid a grid onto the TrakEM2 workspace and panned through the entire volume within each square of the grid, flagging errors and omissions for later confirmation and segmentation. Generally, new PSDs and new astrocytic branches (sometimes quite large), were discovered during QC. Segmentation of thin astrocytic processes was stopped when astrocytic membranes could not be differentiated from one another. In a number of such cases, it did appear that the astrocytic membrane was simply pinched, rendering the process too thin to be resolved, thus a small number of processes may extend further than the segmented volume shows.\n\n## Astrocytic parts decomposition\n\nWater-tight meshes were initially generated from binary segmentation masks using the isosurface function in MATLAB. Voxel sizes were resampled from $[4.13,4.13,8] \\mathrm{nm}$ to $[4,4,4] \\mathrm{nm}$. The meshes were then decimated to $1 \\%$ of the original face count using gptoolbox (decimate_libigl function; https://github.com/alecjacobson/gptoolbox). A local thickness value T was then assigned to each mesh vertex by association with the radius of the maximally inscribed sphere within the object, or equivalently, the distance to the closest medial surface point. ${ }^{55} \\mathrm{~A}$ \"bump\" score B was assigned by measuring the Euclidean distance between a vertex and the weighted average of the coordinates of the other vertices in its 15 -hop neighborhood. To avoid errors due to small local perturbations in the mesh arising from segmentation and alignment artifacts, the mesh vertex locationswere smoothed (Gaussian, $\\sigma=3$; 10x) prior to bump score calculation.\n\nThe local thickness and bump score values were then combined in a protrusion measure $P$, to identify the tips of astrocytic processes. We first normalized these scores to lie between 0 and 1, resulting in scaled thickness and bump scores, Ts and Bs. The"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "protrusion score was then defined as $\\mathrm{P}=\\mathrm{Bs} *(1-\\mathrm{Ts})$. This allowed the score to reach maximal values at the tips of thin astrocytic processes. Vertices with $\\mathrm{P}>0.5$ were considered to be process- or branch-tips.\n\nBeginning from each branch-tip, we simulated a region-growing surface flow that ultimately allowed us to assign part types (core, expansion, constriction) and boundaries to patches of the mesh. The surface flow procedure was designed to halt at core regions. Approximate \"seed core regions\" were first assigned as regions with $\\mathrm{P}<0.15$ ( P -scores smoothed with $20 x$ Gaussian blur, $\\sigma=3$ ) and Ts>0.9 (Ts smoothed with 10x Gaussian blur, $\\sigma=3$ ). This identified thick regions with relatively flat boundaries. A front was then evolved independently from each branch tip, by including the previously unvisited 1-hop neighbours of the vertices in the present front, at each iteration. The growing front was also required to contain an element of the shortest path from the branch-tip to the nearest core to prevent side arms from being followed. This process was repeated until a core was reached. Arrays containing summary Ts values for the set of vertices for each iteration of front evolution were stored. Empirical derivatives of curves describing changes in local thickness along the path of the evolving front were then used to find inflection points in the rate of change of the thickness. Inflection points and the magnitudes of the $3^{\\text {rd }}$ derivatives were used to define boundaries between adjacent thicker and thinner parts (expansions and constrictions, respectively). Each surface flow process created a model that assigned vertices in a subregion of the mesh as either \"expansion\", \"constriction\" or \"unassignable\" such that models overlapped. Thus, a consensus model was generated with vertex assignment prioritizing expansion identity, followed by constriction identity, followed by unassignable identity. In other words, vertices labelled expansion in any surface flow were labelled as expansion vertices in the final model. Vertices labelled constriction in at least one surface flow, but never labelled expansion, were labelled constriction in the final model. Vertices only labelled unassignable were left unassigned. Finally, seed core regions were grown outward to all connected vertices with Ts<0.9, to label the final core regions.\n\n## Loop detection\n\nWe generated medial curve skeletons for voxelized astrocytic volumes using topology invariant thinning. ${ }^{88,89}$ The curve skeletons were then converted to a graph with vertices at each skeleton voxel and edges between adjacent voxels in the 26 neighbourhood. We edited the graph by removing intermediate vertices along linear chain regions. This reduced the size of the graph without changing the topology, making the algorithms much faster and feasible to run on our large volumes. We then computed the spanning tree of the skeleton graph using Kruskal's algorithm. All the edges not contained in the spanning tree were identified as part of a putative loop. The corresponding loops for each edge were computed using a simple depth-first search on the graph constructed from the spanning tree with the edge included. In the graphical representation, the astrocyte is represented as a directed acyclic graph (DAG). Loops in DAGs were identified by inspecting the indegree of nodes. Nodes with indegree greater than 1 were marked as parts of a multi-part loop. The entire loop was then reconstructed by backtracking to the lowest common ancestor, keeping track of each edge on the paths.\n\n## PSDSegmentation and profiling\n\nWe manually segmented all PSDs contacted by segmented astrocytes in reference volumes. PSDs were considered to be associated with the astrocyte if the PAP made contact anywhere on the synaptic unit (defined as the synaptic cleft, spine head, spine neck and axonal bouton). ${ }^{91}$ For shaft synapses, since the variable size of the postsynaptic dendrites meant that the postsynaptic compartment could be very large, only shaft synapses contacted on the axonal varicosity or at the synaptic cleft were considered. Only PSDs that had clear symmetric or asymmetric dark staining and had at least three apparent vesicles were segmented. ${ }^{90}$ Nearly all PSDs were associated with many docked and undocked vesicles. In each reference volume, a small proportion of PSDs were omitted from analyses as they were cut off at the edge of the volume and hence partial or distorted due to FIB-milling artifacts. PSDs were categorized by: 1) their location (spine, dendritic shaft, cell body); 2) their type (asymmetric or symmetric); 3) the presence or absence of a spine apparatus (SA); 4) whether they were macular or perforated; 5) whether they were associated with endoplasmic reticulum (ER) at the PSD, spine base or in the spine neck.\n\n## Geodesic distance measurements\n\nWe used a fast marching method ${ }^{21}$ to solve the eikonal equation both inside and outside the segmented astrocytes to compute distance from mitochondria to PSDs. Mitochondrial surfaces were used as the initial wave-front inside the astrocytic volume, and the astrocytic surface was used as the initial wave-front outside the astrocytic volume. The fast marching approach allowed us to evolve the initial surfaces to compute distance from mitochondria at every point inside the astrocyte volume (Video S4) and from the astrocyte surface to every point outside the astrocyte (Videos S1, S2, and S3). We assumed a constant isotropic metric everywhere inside and outside the astrocytic surface. To compute shortest paths, we use gradient descent on the computed distance map.\n\n## Mitochondria, ER and MERC Analysis\n\nMitochondria, sections of ER, and MERCs were reconstructed manually using TrakEM2. MERCs were identified as sections of ER membrane that were separated less than 30 nm from the outer mitochondrial membrane, with an electron dense cleft between the organelles. ${ }^{91}$ The contact points between the ER and outer mitochondrial membrane were used to determine the length of MERCs. Triangulated meshes of reconstructed organelles were exported from TrakEM2 as wavefront.obj files and imported into Blender or MATLAB for analysis. We used the NeuroMorph Blender plugin ${ }^{18}$ to obtain surfaces and volume of manually reconstructed mitochondria. Vertices located on the edges of the image stack were manually excluded prior to analysis to avoid artifacts. To"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "estimate the surface area of manually segmented MERCs, the surfaces of the 3D object, which faced mitochondria, were manually selected and measured using NeuroMorph.\n\nSurface curvatures for reconstructed mitochondria and ER were computed using the MATLAB Graph Theory Toolbox. ${ }^{92}$ Meshes were smoothed to reduce segmentation artifacts by applying a combinatorial Laplacian operator. ER surface points were clustered based on their total curvature ( $\\mid \\mathrm{k} 1\\{+\\mid \\mathrm{k} 2\\}$ ). A 3-component Gaussian mixture model was fit to the ER surface curvature data using the fitgmdist function in MATLAB (1000 iterations, 10 replicates). Surface vertices were labeled based on this model. To account for the very different size of reconstructed ER datasets, we combined random samples of equal size from each dataset as input to the fitting function. ER curvature calculations and clustering were performed on the GRAHAM(GP3) computing cluster at the University of Waterloo, through the Compute Canada (www.computecanada.ca) network.\n\nMitochondrial local thickness was computed from binary images using the local thickness plugin in FIJI. For each mitochondrion we computed the average value of the distance map output obtained from this plugin.\n\n# Dominant sets clustering \n\nMost clustering methods, such as k-means, seek a strict partition of the entities into disjoint sets. We chose instead to use the dominant sets (Dsets) clustering algorithm ${ }^{55,93,94}$ which provides a formal definition of a cluster for each set of PSDs grouped and allows for a clear theoretical interpretation of the results. This method requires as input a measure of pairwise similarity between each pair of entities. These similarities are expressed in terms of the entries in an adjacency matrix. The method then finds clusters with two guarantees. First, entities (PSDs) within the same cluster have a high degree of internal coherence, i.e., there is a high degree of similarity between any pair of PSDs within the same cluster. Second, the clusters are locally maximal, in that no cluster can be absorbed within a larger one, without decreasing the average pairwise similarities.\n\nOur application of the DSets algorithm used a similarity score that is inversely proportional to the geodesic distances between pairs of PSDs either within the astrocyte volume (intra-volume distance) or along the surface of the astrocytes (surface distance). We associated each PSDto the closest point on the astrocyte surface. Geodesic distance was then computed between points on astrocyte surface closest to each PSDusing fast marching. To compute pairwise distance from each PSDsurface point to every other PSDsurface point on the astrocyte, we repeated the process with every PSDas the starting point. We experimented with several monotonically decreasing functions of geodesic distance in constructing the similarity weights of the adjacency matrix, all of which gave essentially the same results.\n\nIn addition to its theoretical guarantee that each cluster is a dominant set, the algorithm provides additional advantages for clustering PSDs. The number of clusters is derived from the data itself - there is no requirement that this be specified a priori. Furthermore, for our case of symmetric affinities, the solutions are maximizers of a quadratic function and can be efficiently found by using an appropriate dynamical system. In practice, both replicator dynamics and infection and immunization dynamics ${ }^{93,94}$ give the same results while the latter is more efficient for large problem sizes.\n\n## QUANTIFICATION AND STATISTICAL ANALYSIS\n\nStatistical analyses and data representation were performed using Origin (OriginLab, Northampton MA), Matlab (MathWorks, Natick MA) and R (R Core Team, 2021). R packages used included ggplot2, tidyverse, lemon, scales, igraph, OmnipathR, and dbscan. Unless otherwise noted, mean comparisons were performed using Student's t-test or ANOVA and 2-Way ANOVA with Tukey HSD pairwise comparisons, preceded by the Shapiro-Wilk normality test."
